segments.text: We're just moving too quick to cancel people, to ruin people's lives, to go by hearsay, to trial without a jury, trial without a trial, you know, to condemn people.
I just think we need to slow down.
And I really lament that social media has so much power.
You know, it's just opinions.
It's all opinions.

Patti Smith, rock and roll icon, godmother of New York punk, writer, artist, singer, maker of the legendary album Horses, writer of songs like People Have the Power, Dancing Barefoot, Because of the Night, author of the award-winning bestseller Just Kids, a memoir of her relationship with the photographer and artist Robert Mablethorpe.
friend of Bob Dylan, Janis Joplin, Lou Reed, pretty much all the rock and roll legends of the last 50 years.
I met Patty at Electric Lady Studios in New York.
The studios opened by Jimi Hendrix in 1970, just weeks before his death.
We went upstairs and we sat alone in a room together and talked about life as an artist today compared to the 1970s.
We talked about cancel culture and the problematic Picasso.
We talked about famous friends who have come and gone.
And we talked about why she considers herself a writer above all else.
I hope you enjoy this conversation as much as I did.
Welcome to The Act of Voice.
I'm Hamish McKenzie, and here is Patti Smith.
Patti Smith, thank you so much for talking to me and being on The Active Voice.
We're in an amazing place.
We're in Electric Lady Studios, where you recorded horses and a bunch of other things.
Yes.
And I thought I might just start off by asking you what this place means to you.
Well, for me, it's the soul of the recording industry.
It's the house that Jimi Hendrix built, and it's built within a building that has housed vaudeville music, has housed club music, has housed the great painter and teacher Hans Hoffman.
some of the action painters, or the abstract expressionists.
And then Jimi Hendrix took it over, built the studio, and had a beautiful vision.
He really wanted to create, get musicians from all over the world, record together, find a common language.
And he believed that together, people from all over the world, musicians, could create the language of peace through music.
Like Beethoven, who believed, you know, music was the language of God.

So when I come in here to record, whether it's talking to you or doing a new song or whatever my task is, I'm always grateful, you know, to be here and conscious of its history and even my own history here.
I recorded my first independent single, Piss Factory, here in 74.
So I have a long history with the studio.
You were here for the opening, you're telling me, 1970?
Yes, I was here for the opening in August 1970.
Jimmy was on his way to the Isle of Wight and he opened up the studio and that's how I know what his vision was because I got to meet him on the stairwell because I was too shy to go into the party.
I was only around 22 or, you know, however old I was.
You know, I was a little hesitant to go in and he stopped and talked to me and told me that he was also shy and we talked about his vision for the studio.
I never thought that I'd ever record.
I had no thoughts of recording.
I didn't imagine that I'd have a rock and roll band.
I was writing poetry.

And then I wound up recording my first album and it always, it was sort of beautiful but heartbreaking when we started recording to realize that he had such visions for the studio, never got to realize them.
And here we were in the same studio.
Did you feel some sort of debt to Jimmy being in that space?
Yes.
I felt a debt to his vision.
I felt a debt to the fact that he wanted to do new things.
He wanted to break ground.
He wanted to bring people together.
And I always feel that debt.
And it's a good debt, though.
It's not a burden.
It's a good one.
Do you agree with that sentiment that music is the language of the gods or the language of peace, whatever the phrase was?
Well, I mean, I don't adhere to any specific thing.
Some people say that poetry is, some people say dance.
You know, I think they're all beautiful.
And in the past, you've said that if you had to choose between music or between rock and writing, it wouldn't be a hard choice and that you would go with writing.
Am I interpreting that correctly?
No, that's right.
I mean, I love, really love performing and I love the connection with the people.
And I feel privileged to have recorded like 12 albums.
But always since I was a child, I wanted to write.
I've always loved books.
And, you know, I could live
And I've already proved it to myself.
I can live without performing, I can live without creating records, but I can't live without writing.
I write every day, you know, something.
I wrote this morning before I met you and it's part of who I am.
It's part of my daily practice.
What does it do for you?
Well, I mean, first of all, I have a very active mind and it allows me to, you know, it's like a river of stories and a torrent sometimes of stories and thoughts and ideas.
And it allows me to, you know, to, you know, empty myself and give them to others.
But it just makes me happy.
It makes me feel like I'm contributing something.
And sometimes, even though it might sound conceited, sometimes I write stuff that I just like reading.
I'll write to entertain myself, because I only publish maybe a tenth of what I write.
So a lot of my writing is just keeping up with the craft of writing, developing my skills, just writing because my imagination is flowing into my pen.
And some of it is just a learning process, writing the same paragraph, sometimes 15 times till you get it where you want it to be.
You know, a lot of writing is excruciating, laborious and tedious, but sometimes it's just exhilarating.
Like, you know, how it must have, you know,
All creation is exhilarating, whether it's painting or you come upon a lyric or improvise in front of thousands of people and you can tell you're on a roll.
It can be very exciting and it can be a great burden.
What do you mean by burden?
Well, it's sometimes, you know, if like, because writing is such always been such a part of me, it makes it hard to just live.
You know, also, like, if you're a photographer, you just want to look at the desert or you want to, you know, walk down the street, but you can't help.
freezing this moment or taking this shot because you're compelled to do it.
You see the shot.
And so you can't just simply walk down the street, you know, or writing.
I could be at a party or I could have, I can be at the opera.
I can be somewhere where I really want to be, but something triggers my mind.
So I always keep a notebook in my pocket.
Sometimes writing in the dark and often things I can't decipher because I'll write words on top of words.
But sometimes I just, I'm so grateful to have a vocation that I've had and chose very early in life.
Every once in a while I just wish I could just, you know, I could just proceed.
I could just not, you know, want to turn everything into something else.
But that's what artists do.
Robert Mapplethorpe and I used to talk about that.
I remember once, you know, we had no money and we were walking somewhere at night.
And someone had left a pair of alligator shoes.
I don't know if they stole them or what brand new, really expensive, beautiful, glowing alligator shoes on the sidewalk.
And Robert, we stood there and looked at them.
And we had this little game and I'd say, life or art?
And he said, if they fit me both, which just meant it was he going to put them in an installation?
What was it?
Did they fit him?
Well, they were a little big, but he stuffed a lot of toilet paper at the end of them and he wore them occasionally.
But then they found their way into an installation.
But yeah, we used to have that little game, life or art, you know.
And you walked in here with a notebook.
And apparently I scheduled this interview.
And during your usual daily practice of writing time, does that mean you're writing like pen and paper most of the time?
Oh yeah, I always write, yeah, I write by hand.
Beautiful handwriting for people who can't see this, which is everyone.
Very tidy all the way through and tight.
Yes, I have really nice handwriting, but I worked at it.
But I was also raised in, you know, early fifties and penmanship was an important part of our education.
I learned how to write with a nib, you know, quill and an inkwell.
And until I was in second or third grade, then we went to pencil.
What was that transition like?
I know that's a random question, but going from quill writing to pencil writing.
Well, less ink on my clothing because I was very sloppy, but I was very taken with that.
I wasn't really skilled at first with that.
It's very hard to get just the right amount of ink in your nib.
But later, you know, when I got a little older, I would try to copy the Declaration of Independence because
That's why I have such good handwriting, because I wanted to write like that.
You know, I'd look at these... The visual style.
It was a visual thing, yes.
But I write in my notebooks and then transcribe them later.
Actually, I hate transcribing, so Lenny K helps me.
He's always helped me transcribe because he's a really fast typer.
And Lenny K, of course, is my guitarist and great friend for half a century.
And even in the 70s, he would, sometimes I would write orally and we would sit and he would just type it out.
Oh, wow.
What a great friend.
Yeah, he's, you know, we have different ways of helping one another.
And for instance, I'm working on a book and I write every day and then in the afternoon I call him and he gets his computer and I read it to him over the phone because he's in Pennsylvania.
And then he sends me the document and then I can edit it.
So, you know, I used to transcribe my own things and occasionally I do but I'm really slow and it's very, I find it tedious and it makes me lose interest, you know.
I like to edit on the computer because then I don't have to write the same paragraph over and over and over.
I can see it in different forms.
Why do you think he does that?
Why does he do that for you?
He's my friend.
Well, because he knows, I mean, we started doing that in 77.
I had a really bad accident and I was unable to- Is this when you fell off the stage?
Yeah, I had a spinal accident and I'd like fractured several bones in my spine and I couldn't do anything.
And I got my first big poetry book.
I got like a $10,000 to do it.
a major poetry book and I couldn't write so I had to figure out how to, we didn't have any money and so it was a way to, I think I was going to get a $5,000 advance, which was a lot of money then.
So Lenny would bring his typewriter
and sit by my bed and he would sit there because I couldn't figure out what to do because my mind was working fine.
And I just orally, I did a book called Babble and it was my first big poetry book.
And Lenny just sat there and typed out, you know, he'd smoke a little pot and then we'd sit there.
I'd be laying there and babbling away.
And then we just, you know, he just became the person who did that.
When we'd write manifestos, I'd write them by hand and he'd type them out.
I'm just such a slow typer.
You know, I typed a lot when I was younger, but in my own time, you know, but he's a speed typer.
You know, he was like one of these people that,
I don't know how he does it, he just flies.
But he does it because we do things for each other.
We both excel in different things and so we help one another.
In a way, it's a lot like writing songs.
I mean, we wrote a lot of songs together.
Ghost Dance and Free Money and Jubilee and Fuji-san.
I mean, lots and lots of songs.
And it's sort of the same.
He writes the chords and I write the words.
And so it's just a different way to collaborate.
I have a naive question for you, which makes me seem a little silly, I think.
It's okay.
I'm 41, you turned 76 not so long ago, and you've had this relationship with him, like Lenny was with you for your first poetry recital.
Yeah, since February 71, yeah.
So my naive question is, what's it like to have a friendship like that, that's spanned the decades and has been so close and collaborative?
Well, it's great.
I mean, the best part about it is he's alive because I was fortunate.
I mean, I would have had the same.
I met Robert Mapplethorpe before Lenny, Sam Shepard before Lenny.
I collaborated with both of them and imagined I would know them for my whole life.
You know, and later my husband.
I've lost a lot of people that I really loved and had a strong relationship with and a collaborative relationship.
So I'm so grateful that Lenny and I were only three days apart.
We were both born in late December of 46.
And it's not just collaboration, it's shared memory.
He knew Fred, he knew Sam, he knew Robert, he knew all my children.
So I have a friend that's still with us that we have shared memory.
So we're both that to each other.

And also you have so many references, you have so many references, you only have to say one or two words that make nothing, you know, I might say, ugh, baby sauce, and we'll both start laughing because it means it has so many layers of meaning.
You know, and also, you know, it's just, even though we help each other, it's, you know, friendship at its best is both, you know, people are mutually helping each other, but it's also unconditional.
We don't have meters, like who's helping who the most or, you know, it's not like that.
What's it like to, you mentioned a list of people and that's only a partial list of people you've been very close with who have died.
And, you know, another one is your brother, Todd, and your pianist, Richard.
How do you go through so much of that and how does it affect how you see life?
It doesn't affect how I see life, I don't think.
I mean, I live my life.
I understand, you know, the whole package.
I mean, as soon as you're old enough to understand part of the package of life is you will also die.
I understand the package and, you know, accept that.
Losing my people, it's different with all of them because they, each person might've provided different things.
Sometimes I feel like the regret, like my pianist, Richard Soule, he was the best accompanist I ever had.
You know, he just, he didn't write music or write, but he anticipated
on piano every move I made.
He was like Billie Holiday's Teddy Wilson, you know, and it makes me sad because my husband loved working with him.
We all loved working with him.
He was beloved and he was beautiful and he was beloved.
You know, it's still, I have my bass player, Tony Shanahan, actually, he plays everything, has worked so hard to give me some piano accompaniment with a person I'm comfortable for.
But Richard is, you know, we all hail Richard's memory.
And with my husband, it's too much to talk about.
It's unfathomable how much losing him has impacted my life, you know.
And also having, you know, two children, young children, when he passed away.
And my brother, you know, missing Robert, because Robert and I would have kept, Robert and I would have done so many things, you know, so many.
You know, it's, you know, I look around at the landscape of, you know, all these people and the work they would have created independently and things we would have done on our own.
Sam Shepard actually lived the longest.
And, you know, I always, Sam and I always imagined we'd
grow old and be like, you know, old Samuel Beckett characters writing away until we were 90.
I really expected that.
So, yeah, it's, you know, I have kids who are awesome and I have new friends, which I'm grateful for, but
I don't know, you just, I'm grateful to be alive.
I love being alive.
I love working and seeing new things.
I still have great enthusiasm for new work, new films people make, new books people write, whatever I can possibly do.
So, you know, I guess it all comes down to gratitude.
You know, you just like have to go through each day thinking what you have to be grateful for.
that day and I have a lot.
My mother always taught us the value of relativity.
She always said this thing, I've said this before, but it's like ingrained in my mind.
When I was a kid, my shoes were in ill repair and my family didn't have any money to get me a new pair of shoes.
And I was maybe sad about that.
And my mother said, I went because I had no shoes.
And then I saw a man who had no feet.
And I just looked at her and I was like, I don't know how old I was, maybe seven or eight.
And I was like, oh, it permeated.
But her whole thing is no matter what you think one lacks, you don't have enough food or whatever you think your strife is, there are people out there who wish they were as lucky as you.

Yeah, this statement you said, I love living, it's very simple, but it's actually something that's easy to take for granted, or that people don't give much thought to, but is it something you consciously cultivate?
Well, I don't need to cultivate it, it just is.
I mean, I was, you know, in fact, one of my favorite lines in all of rock and roll is Jimi Hendrix's line, hooray, I wake from yesterday.
Hooray, I wake from yesterday.
I was just like,
I love that, you know, it's just like R.E.M.
's song, it's the end of the world as we know it, but I feel fine.

Another great line, you know, and I just think of these two lines because one, I'm sort of old fashioned and I do mourn a lot of the changes in our world and how cultural changes and just all kinds of changes.
Things are not exactly peachy right now.
Well, it's also just how change, you know, economic change, architectural change, it could be anything.
But these two lines, you know, Michael's line and Jimi Hendrix line, they're two good mantras.
Back to the writing for a bit.
You had to, maybe I'm reading too much into this, maybe, but

It seems like you had to fight to be a writer a little bit because when you were young you had some eye trouble or health issue that made it so it was physically difficult to write and read your own writing and you had to write the letters backwards and upside down.
Is that correct?
No, I did write, I mirror wrote because I had such a, I forget the name of it, but I have like a severe lazy eye muscle in my right eye.
And when I was young, I had to wear an eye patch because it was so
I had like lizard eyes, you know.
But yeah, that made writing itself frustrating, but not thought, you know.
So I would make up stories in my head.
I was too young to, the idea that stories would evaporate if you didn't write them down didn't
You know, I hadn't thought of that yet.
I wasn't, I made up stories in my head all the time.
And if I lost one, there was a new story.
So, no, my struggles weren't really that.
My struggles are just because I'm not, I was very resistant to learning mechanics, grammar, sentence structure, all the things that we had to do.
I just, my mind could not grasp all of that.
And it all seemed spelling, all these things that I made mistakes on in my papers or stories we had to write for school, I would always get a great mark in imagination and a fair mark in execution.
And to this day, I have to, I'm much better, but I have to sometimes go to a dictionary or go to a thesaurus or just read other people's sentences to see how do you use a semicolon?
Because I can't quite.
No one knows how to use a semicolon.
But I mean, it's really everything with me.
I can't say that I was,
You know, I've never been a prodigy, you know, it's just I'm not a prodigy.
I've known them, but I have a strong will and I am a hard worker and I have a good imagination.
So it's taken me years and years and years of daily practice to get to a point where I am now, where I feel I'm happy with my writing.
I mean, I still struggle with it.
I still struggle with saying exactly what I mean or going through the various choices, especially with poetry.
Poetry drives me crazy.
That's why I don't even write it so much, but sometimes I can't resist.
But the amount of choices that we have in this coded language, sometimes it makes me, you know, crazy.
I feel like I wish I could write
four parallel poems at the same time, because my mind is seeing four different ways constantly to say the same thing.
How are you choosing what to spend time on when it comes to writing these days?
Because you're still writing books.
You serialized The Melting, which is about the pandemic experience, and you've written a bunch of other books.
You wrote this legendary book, Just Kids, about your relationship with Robert Mapplethorpe.
Is there any conscious choice you just go with the flow?
Well, I try, I mean, I try to, I'm trying to write a book right now, which is, you know, a book like, it's another memoir.
And that's really important.
I've been thinking about this for the past few years.
And I keep interrupting myself, like during the pandemic, the melting, I haven't even finished the melting on my sub stack, because I have pages and pages that I have to,
I just have to pull it together and end it.
I know how it's going to end, but it's like the labor to do it.

And also it became very upsetting because as I was writing it so much about climate disasters in time, the disasters I was writing about as nonfiction, I mean, as fiction were happening and worse right in front of my, and it started making me actually feel sick.
So I just had to, my poor subscribers, they're very patient.
But then it's the same thing.
I'm trying, I saw this movie, The Green Knight, awesome movie that inspired me to write a very long Sibaldian poem.
called Green, and I'm trying to write that.
I'm going to publish it first on my sub stack.

But my readers are condemned to, you know, have to go through my lengthy process, and sometimes the fact that that poem is now interrupted by another thing that came into my head, and then I'm writing another thing.

Like in this notebook, I'm trying to just stay, use the notebook to write about one subject, but already it's been permeated by an insane story that was probably prompted because I watch a lot of these Korean dramas, you know, these long series.
They're like the soap operas.
Well, they're like from like, I don't know what century, 16th century, I don't know, but they're like historical.
But there's one called Alchemy of Souls, and it's as good as the title.
You know, and it's like they've great, great actors, just such great stories that are like romance and fantasy and
and skills and martial arts and, you know, sorcery, but it's all, you know, so beautifully laid out.
And so I think I wound up starting to write a story like that as I'm trying to write about, you know, 1964.
So it was, it's challenging.
It's challenging because I've always found it difficult to just do one thing.
What part of your life is this memoir focused on?
A lot of it is childhood, but I don't want to talk about that one because I really need not to talk about it.
Just do it.
But I'm always working on multiple projects.
That's just how I am.
It's just like vocations.
I've often said I wish, you know, I could be like Joan Mitchell.
She was a painter, you know, a great painter.
And she said that once.
Well, I'm a painter.
That's what I do.
That's all.
I'm just a painter.
And if I could just say that, I'm just a writer or I'm just a performer or, you know, I'm just a gardener.
But I have, you know, multiple vocations and all seem that they call on me for a different time.
But I try to fit as much in as possible.
You're doing quite a good job of that.
This podcast is about how writers' lives and work are affected by the internet.
And when I think of Patti Smith, at least 10 years ago, when I thought of Patti Smith, I wouldn't have thought, she's going to be an internet person.
She's going to be on Instagram.
She's going to be on Substack.
And I wonder how that came into your life.
Well, I don't really, I mean for me, I know that they're within the internet, but because I'm not really, I don't really engage much in the internet, and I never really did.
You know, I have like no Twitter, no this or that.
Never start a Twitter, that would be the answer.
No, I never, actually I have, this is really a funny, sort of a stupid story, but it's true.

When I did an album, like maybe 10 years ago, I don't know when Twitter started, but I didn't have any idea what Twitter, I didn't have any idea what any of these things were because I just, I had no internet consciousness.
And the publicists wanted me to, at my record company, they had young people and they wanted me to start a Twitter account.
I had no idea.
I said, I don't want to do that.
I don't want to, I don't want to have it.
It's not my thing.
And they said,
All right.
And I said, I don't even know how to do it.
And they said, you just have to write down 18 characters.
So I thought, so one night I thought 18 characters.
Okay.
So I, I wrote down 18 characters, Ahab, Pinocchio, Peter Pan.
I was thinking, well, this could be fun.
Is this a true story?
This is a true story.
Cause no one, I had no idea, never saw a Twitter and I thought 18 characters.
So I thought it was maybe some kind of thing where you introduce characters and maybe you had to say something.
That's a much better version of Twitter.
I wish that one existed.
So I wrote them and sent them in and they were just like, when it came down to when I figured out and they explained to me what it was and I said, this is like writing haiku poetry.
I tried it like once or twice and I said, I can't do this.
I just, I just can't do it.
I'm not, I don't want to talk to people with 18 words, you know, it's like, and also I don't want them talking to me.
I just, I just, so I never did that.
I only did Instagram because my daughter has an Instagram and she, I had no idea there was this whole jungle out there, good and bad.
And she said, you know, there's a lot of people because you're not claiming your name who are claiming your name.
And some of them are actually soliciting people for money and, you know, giving a telephone number and saying, you know, I'll talk to you personally for this amount of money.
These poor people.
And so she said, I should start my own and get a blue check.
And then people would know it was mine and get rid of all the imposters.
She showed me how to do it, and it was really sort of up my alley, because all I had to do was show a picture, and I take pictures all the time.
I've taken thousands of pictures.
And it could be a Polaroid, or it could be a picture that you took, you know, out in the street, and write a little something.
So I thought, well, that could be nice.
And actually,
Yes, I'm involved in the internet, but always in my own way.
I started my Instagram, I made it my own way, it looks my own way, and my preoccupations are my own, and I don't allow or I just get rid of when people are
provocative or want to start fighting or politically or want to try to sell, you know, some kind of, you know, shares in something or offering people money.
I try to keep it clean.
It's not always possible, but I try to keep it clean.
You've got a million people following you on Instagram now.
I don't know how that happened.
My daughter was my first.
And I said, oh, Jessie, that's so nice.
I have a follower.
She said, yes, it's me, mommy, but it's going to it's going to change.
Before we knew it, it grew so fast.
You know, I was really surprised.

And then the pandemic happened and I felt I felt like the thing that I like about my Substack and my besides them being creative outlets and my Instagram, when the pandemic started, I was supposed to go on a world tour with my band.
It had been planned for a year.
We were going everywhere from Australia to, you know, everywhere, Europe and Scandinavia, a whole year.
And it was shut down like days, only days before.
I mean, literally days, like March 20th, I think everything was shut down and we were supposed to go on the road like March 25th or something.
But it was like that, all of a sudden the door was slammed.
So suddenly, you know, I was 73 or whatever, and with a bronchial condition, which is chronic, and I've had it since a kid.
And so I was high risk.

So I went from going to see the world with my little suitcase to being totally confined and also going from, you know, as a writer, it's very solitary, but when I'm on the road, that's my public life.
That's when I'm engaging with the people.
And all of a sudden I was confined and really confined to saw nobody but my daughter.
For how long?
For two years.
Wow.
In the prime of your life as well, Patty.
Yeah, in the prime of my life.
So, yeah, two years we had no work and it kept filtering on to the third year.
But I found having, you know, doing the small interaction there is,

with the Instagram and then certainly the sub stack, having people comment, not in a mean way or putting things down or misinformation, but talking about things like writing or, you know, maybe a little childhood recollection or even just giving me a compliment, whatever, whatever it is.
It kept me engaged with the people in the world.

My connection in the internet to me in terms of my own contribution to me has been, it's not going to change the world, not going to break any barriers, but it does give people a place where they're going to either be entertained

aesthetically, or just because I'm reading them Uncle Wiggly, or, you know, taking them on some little shaggy dog excursion, which I will do, or sitting there with my cat, or suggesting really great books that might be a little obscure and translations.

Another cool thing you've done is give people a look behind the scenes when you're on tour, like a tour of the quarters you're staying in or the backstage area, which is nice and it's hard to access for normies like me.
It feels like you're in communion with people.
No, I like to do that, but also show them my process.
I'm going to start this thing for my subscribers.
I sort of started it with this poem.
I was joking that I had my little symposium, my writer's symposium, and one of the comments was from somebody named Frederick W., I think, and he said, it's a Smithposium.
And I thought, that's great.
So now I'm starting my Smithposium.
And one of the things that I want to do this week is just, for instance, show my subscribers how a song is written.
Awesome.
where the idea came from.
A song I wrote myself, which I don't write a lot because... From the archives, you mean?
